>>40732438
I'd say that removed from writing quality I really like the idea of this story. You've got several issues though. There are a couple spelling and grammatical errors but that stuff's easy enough to fix on your own. I have a problem with the way that you write. I honestly couldn't boil your problem down to one thing, so here's a list: show don't tell, setups, and character writing.
>Show don't tell
You have a habit of telling the audience what's happening in the story in a very blatant way, which detracts from your pacing quite a bit. You write stuff like
>The monster yells out at you in distress.
As if we couldn't gather that from what she just said.
You seem to have an issue with being concise, you talk about Joe's presentation, how it takes an hour and a half and you say that he'd woken up early to do more research, but as readers having seen none of that it's mostly pointless. And given that what should be a relatively short presentation took Joe an hour and 30 minutes, it seems like he has a problem with being concise too.
>Setup and payoff
You have an issue with embellishing when it doesn't really benefit anyone to do so. You have a whole section on The Office and Joe's vs Loka's preference. This would be fine if it resulted in something like a conversation, but you only bring it up for the sake of bringing it up. It serves essentially no purpose, as it isn't used to provide conflict, unity, or really any type of interaction between the two. Later on you talk about horror movies, but the horror movies actually mean something to Loka because she can see how humans view monsters, and she struggles with the idea that she is seen that way by Joe. This has a clear defined purpose, and both creates and solves conflict between the characters, which is well done.

You seem to have an issue with bringing certain things up, you introduce In N Out Burger and GrubHub twice. Not only could you have just said "we're ordering burgers for delivery", the second time you bring up ordering food, it's for the same purpose and in almost the same phrasing as the first time. Personally, I think you should keep the second occurrence and axe the first, it fits better since everyone is actually at the house.
>Character Writing (really moreso just character reactions)
Honestly, reading
>Ow, it was the most painful bite you have ever felt.
this is probably the reason that I'm even posting in the first place. That sentence has so little narrative weight that it almost feels like it was played for a joke. We're talking large and sharp teeth here, and the most he can gather is an measley Ow? This is the same guy who blew up in Loka's face about his insomnia. He doesn't need to be mad at her, but he should have some sort of reaction. He can feel pain, maybe swear or at the very least.
>Personal Gripe
This really isn't an issue with how you write, but I dislike the way that you seem to introduce different things that seem like you just really wanted to write about but have very little connection to the source material. The ESP thing in this chapter was like that, and Chirality earlier, sure they're very slightly interesting, but they do very little in the overall story. Chirality at least had a story purpose, and put a timer on Loka until the tests results came back, but the ESP thing just stirred up an ultimately pointless argument that didn't really further anything. This is just a personal dislike, it's not a critique as much as it is just me complaining.
